{"title_page": "Petraio", "text_new": "The '''Petraio''' is a widely-known geographical and urban area in [[Naples, Italy]], which descends from what was once the expansive upper agricultural area (later becoming the present day hilltop district of [[Vomero]]), connecting with lower neighborhoods along the way, terminating n the [[Chiaia]] neighborhood of downtown Naples. \n\nMostly framed with residential buildings, the Petraio is accessibly only on foot, and is noted for its broad range of architecture, from [[Liberty style|Neapolitan Liberty]] villas to its ''bassi'' (small one and two room dwellings directly accessed off the Petraio itself) &mdash; as well as its picturesque character and sweeping views of the city.\n\n*'''The upper Petraio terminus''': {{coord|40|50|35.8728|N|14|14|10.7016|E|display=inline|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\nFomerly called ''O'Petraro'',<ref name=\"pet5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Ascent of the Petraio\n |publisher    = thesooper.it\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = https://thesooper.it/napoli/luoghi-da-scoprire-a-napoli/aria-aperta/salita-del-petraio/}}</ref>, the interconnected pathways were originally a natural, self-formed alluvial channel that followed a narrow watershed, deposting rocks, stones and pebbles, meandering and bifurcating as it descended. As these areas were gradually trafficked and inhabited, they were improved to a narrow series of interconnected stone paths, walks, alleys, steps and ramps &mdash; varying in slope and width, at points overarched by buildings.<ref name=\"pet8\">{{cite web\n |title        = Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders\n |publisher    = repubblica.it\n |author       = Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata\n |date         = January 14, 2014\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fespresso.repubblica.it%2Fvisioni%2Fcultura%2F2014%2F01%2F14%2Fnews%2Fnapoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref> \n\nIts prominent sections include Gradini (steps) del Petraio, Descesa (descending steps) del Petraio, Vico (alley) del Petraio, Largo (widening) del Petraio, Rampe (ramp) del Petraio, Salita (climb) del Petraio, Via Filippo Palizzi and Via Achille Vianelli. Near one of its many prominent architectural features, Villa Santarella, the Petraio is colloquially called ''La Santarella''. \n\n==Access==\nAt its summit, the Petraio can be accessed via streets in the San Martino section of [[Vomero]], near [[Castel Sant'Elmo]], and at its lower terminus in the area of [[Chiaia]]. The Petraio is served on Via Filippo Palizzi by the ''Palazzolo-Parco Marcolini'' station of the [[Chiaia Funicular]] as well by the ''Petraio'' station of the [[Central Funicular]] at Salita del Petraio and Via Filippo Palizzi.  As well, the Petraio can be accessed by numerous cross-streets, including Naples' prominent Corso Vittorio Emanuele.\n<ref name=\"pet2\">{{cite web\n |title        = Access routes to Vomero: the Petraio and S. Francesco\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = February 5, 2015\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/le-vie-daccesso-al-vomero-il-petraio-s-francesco/}}</ref>  \n\nThe Petraio are a subset of Naples more than 200 neighborhood stairs, ramps and pedestrian descents.<ref>{{cite news|author=Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata |date=14 January 2014 |title=Napoli segreta, le scale delle meraviglie |language=it |trans-title=Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders |newspaper=L'Espresso |url=http://espresso.repubblica.it/visioni/cultura/2014/01/14/news/napoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref>\n\n==[[Paul Klee]]==\nOn his 1901-1902<ref name=\"pet6\">{{cite web\n |title        = The Diaries of Paul Klee, 1898-1918\n |publisher    = University of California Press, 1964\n |author       = Felix Klee, editor\n |date         = \n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> soujourn in Italy, noted Swiss painter [[Paul Klee]] stayed at Pensione Haase<ref name=\"pet1\">{{cite web\n |title        = IL PETRAIO: TRA STORIA E ABBANDONO\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = May 10, 2017\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> (Salita del Petrajo, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples), a Villa directly adjacent to the Petraio.  In his diaries, he compared Geonoa and Naples:\n\n\"It is already impossible for me to even enumerate what I have seen. Compared to Genoa, Naples is indolent, messy and sick. Compared to Naples, Genoa is one-sided. Naples has the greatest splendor alongside the greatest misery. Port life, carriage ride, high-level opera house, even a piece of Rome: the National Museum. Beside this the heavenly nature, unmatched. The sea of \u200b\u200bGenoa more imposing, but also more monotonous. Here a placid cove, framed by strange mountains and closed by characteristic islands. And all I can see from the balcony of my room. Like a giant amphitheater, the wonderful city with its intense buzz lies at my feet. On the left the old city with the docks of the port and the ancient Vesuvius, on the right the modern Villa Nazionale and Posillipo. All around the house there are gardens of fresh green, fantastic shapes and myriads of flowers. Salita del Petraio, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples, is called this fabulous panoramic lookout. The sea is wonderfully blue and calm. The city is a lively picture of clarity, facades of blocks of houses, in the light and darkness, white streets, sections of dark green parks. Faced with such a spectacle one thinks of the temptation of Christ. We are exalted by joy, we are hovering between shining spheres, which have become the center of a world.\"<ref name=\"pet3\">{{cite web\n |title        = Stairs that continue to reveal themselves: the church of the Petraio and the villa where Paul Klee lived\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = Identitainsorgenti.com\n |date         = October 4, 2017\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.identitainsorgenti.com%2Fnapoli-a-piedi-scale-che-continuano-a-svelarsi-la-chiesa-del-petraio-e-la-villa-dove-dimoro-paul-klee%2F}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In the film [[The Four Days of Naples]], in the early stages of the Neapolitan uprising, a young man can be heard shouting: \"Pe 'e criatur' ro Petraio!\".\n*Popularly, the expression salir\u00e8 'ncoppo' is used in Santar\u00e8lla , which indicates the need to go from the Petraio to Villa La Santarella and Piazza Vanvitelli .\n*Author [[Nicola Pugliese]] in his book ''Malacqua'', cites Petraio, describing the origin of his name.\n\n==See Also==\n[[Stairways in Naples]]<br>\n[[Matera]]\n\n{{coord|40|50|35.8728|N|14|14|10.7016|E|display=title|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petraio}}\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Naples]]\n[[Category:Zones of Naples]]\n\n==External References==\n* [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=it&rurl=translate.google.it&sl=it&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.scaledinapoli.com/&usg=ALkJrhjlxbq3eRVLr6oflxJlrzYoms77hA Stairways of Naples]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "text_old": "The '''Petraio''' is a widely-known geographical and urban area in [[Naples, Italy]], which descends from what was once the expansive upper agricultural area (later becoming the present day hilltop district of [[Vomero]]), connecting with lower neighborhoods along the way, terminating n the [[Chiaia]] neighborhood of downtown Naples. \n\nMostly framed with residential buildings, the Petraio is accessibly only on foot, and is noted for its broad range of architecture, from [[Liberty style|Neapolitan Liberty]] villas to its ''bassi'' (small one and two room dwellings directly accessed off the Petraio itself) &mdash; as well as its picturesque character and sweeping views of the city.\n\n*'''The upper Petraio terminus''': {{coord|40|50|35.8728|N|14|14|10.7016|E|display=inline|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\nFomerly called ''O'Petraro'',<ref name=\"pet5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Ascent of the Petraio\n |publisher    = thesooper.it\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = https://thesooper.it/napoli/luoghi-da-scoprire-a-napoli/aria-aperta/salita-del-petraio/}}</ref>, the Petraio was originally a natural, self-formed alluvial channel that followed a narrow watershed, deposting rocks, stones and pebbles, meandering and bifurcating as it descended. As these areas were gradually trafficked and inhabited, they were improved to a narrow series of interconnected stone paths, walks, alleys, steps and ramps &mdash; varying in slope and width, at points overarched by buildings.<ref name=\"pet8\">{{cite web\n |title        = Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders\n |publisher    = repubblica.it\n |author       = Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata\n |date         = January 14, 2014\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fespresso.repubblica.it%2Fvisioni%2Fcultura%2F2014%2F01%2F14%2Fnews%2Fnapoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref> \n\nIts prominent sections include Gradini (steps) del Petraio, Descesa (descending steps) del Petraio, Vico (alley) del Petraio, Largo (widening) del Petraio, Rampe (ramp) del Petraio, Salita (climb) del Petraio, Via Filippo Palizzi and Via Achille Vianelli. Near one of its many prominent architectural features, Villa Santarella, the Petraio is colloquially called ''La Santarella''. \n\n==Access==\nAt its summit, the Petraio can be accessed via streets in the San Martino section of [[Vomero]], near [[Castel Sant'Elmo]], and at its lower terminus in the area of [[Chiaia]]. The Petraio is served on Via Filippo Palizzi by the ''Palazzolo-Parco Marcolini'' station of the [[Chiaia Funicular]] as well by the ''Petraio'' station of the [[Central Funicular]] at Salita del Petraio and Via Filippo Palizzi.  As well, the Petraio can be accessed by numerous cross-streets, including Naples' prominent Corso Vittorio Emanuele.\n<ref name=\"pet2\">{{cite web\n |title        = Access routes to Vomero: the Petraio and S. Francesco\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = February 5, 2015\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/le-vie-daccesso-al-vomero-il-petraio-s-francesco/}}</ref>  \n\nThe Petraio are a subset of Naples more than 200 neighborhood stairs, ramps and pedestrian descents.<ref>{{cite news|author=Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata |date=14 January 2014 |title=Napoli segreta, le scale delle meraviglie |language=it |trans-title=Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders |newspaper=L'Espresso |url=http://espresso.repubblica.it/visioni/cultura/2014/01/14/news/napoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref>\n\n==[[Paul Klee]]==\nOn his 1901-1902<ref name=\"pet6\">{{cite web\n |title        = The Diaries of Paul Klee, 1898-1918\n |publisher    = University of California Press, 1964\n |author       = Felix Klee, editor\n |date         = \n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> soujourn in Italy, noted Swiss painter [[Paul Klee]] stayed at Pensione Haase<ref name=\"pet1\">{{cite web\n |title        = IL PETRAIO: TRA STORIA E ABBANDONO\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = May 10, 2017\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> (Salita del Petrajo, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples), a Villa directly adjacent to the Petraio.  In his diaries, he compared Geonoa and Naples:\n\n\"It is already impossible for me to even enumerate what I have seen. Compared to Genoa, Naples is indolent, messy and sick. Compared to Naples, Genoa is one-sided. Naples has the greatest splendor alongside the greatest misery. Port life, carriage ride, high-level opera house, even a piece of Rome: the National Museum. Beside this the heavenly nature, unmatched. The sea of \u200b\u200bGenoa more imposing, but also more monotonous. Here a placid cove, framed by strange mountains and closed by characteristic islands. And all I can see from the balcony of my room. Like a giant amphitheater, the wonderful city with its intense buzz lies at my feet. On the left the old city with the docks of the port and the ancient Vesuvius, on the right the modern Villa Nazionale and Posillipo. All around the house there are gardens of fresh green, fantastic shapes and myriads of flowers. Salita del Petraio, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples, is called this fabulous panoramic lookout. The sea is wonderfully blue and calm. The city is a lively picture of clarity, facades of blocks of houses, in the light and darkness, white streets, sections of dark green parks. Faced with such a spectacle one thinks of the temptation of Christ. We are exalted by joy, we are hovering between shining spheres, which have become the center of a world.\"<ref name=\"pet3\">{{cite web\n |title        = Stairs that continue to reveal themselves: the church of the Petraio and the villa where Paul Klee lived\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = Identitainsorgenti.com\n |date         = October 4, 2017\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.identitainsorgenti.com%2Fnapoli-a-piedi-scale-che-continuano-a-svelarsi-la-chiesa-del-petraio-e-la-villa-dove-dimoro-paul-klee%2F}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In the film [[The Four Days of Naples]], in the early stages of the Neapolitan uprising, a young man can be heard shouting: \"Pe 'e criatur' ro Petraio!\".\n*Popularly, the expression salir\u00e8 'ncoppo' is used in Santar\u00e8lla , which indicates the need to go from the Petraio to Villa La Santarella and Piazza Vanvitelli .\n*Author [[Nicola Pugliese]] in his book ''Malacqua'', cites Petraio, describing the origin of his name.\n\n==See Also==\n[[Stairways in Naples]]<br>\n[[Matera]]\n\n{{coord|40|50|35.8728|N|14|14|10.7016|E|display=title|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petraio}}\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Naples]]\n[[Category:Zones of Naples]]\n\n==External References==\n* [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=it&rurl=translate.google.it&sl=it&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.scaledinapoli.com/&usg=ALkJrhjlxbq3eRVLr6oflxJlrzYoms77hA Stairways of Naples]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "name_user": "842U", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petraio"}
{"title_page": "Chanell Stone", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name             = Chanell Stone\n| birth_date       = [[1992]]\n| birth_place      = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n| nationality      = American\n| field            = [[Photography]]\n| alma_mater       = [[California College of the Arts]]\n                   and [[Los Angeles Trade-Technical College]]\n| awards           = 2020 Artist in Residence, Real Time and Space\n2019-2020 Emerging Artist Award, [[Museum of the African Diaspora]], San Francisco\n2018-2019  Purchase Prize Award, [[Center for Photography at Woodstock]]\n| website          = {{URL|https://www.chanellstone.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Chanell Stone''' is an African American [[photographer]] living and working in [[Oakland, California]] known for her \"[https://www.chanellstone.com/natura-negra Natura Negra]\" series.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nStone\u00a0received a [[Bachelor of Fine Arts|B.F.A.]] in [[photography]] from [[California College of the Arts]] in 2019. She received an [[associate degree]] in [[English language|English]] from [[Los Angeles Trade-Technical College]] in 2017. \n\n== Work ==\nChanell Stone's work predominantly features black and white self-portraits. She first took an [[analog photography]] class in high school<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/young-photographers-to-follow-2020/|title=These Are the 8 Young Photographers to Follow in 2020|website=W Magazine {{!}} Women's Fashion & Celebrity News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> and continues to use film in her practice, primarily shooting with a Pentax.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nStone was a featured photographer in [[W (magazine)|W Magazine]]'s \"These Are the 8 Young Photographers to Follow in 2020\".<ref name=\":0\" />  She attributes her interest in representation and self-portraiture to growing up with social media, namely [[Myspace]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nHer series \"Natura Negra\" explores the connection of black bodies and nature, specifically the nature that can be found in dense cities<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/arts/13873630/the-faces-and-conversations-of-moads-winter-2020-opening-reception|title=The Faces and Conversations of MoAD's Winter Opening Reception|website=KQED|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> or what she refers to as \"urban nature\".<ref name=\":0\" /> This series sets out to reclaim and reconnect black bodies to nature, even if it is in an urban setting.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.moadsf.org/exhibition/moad-emerging-artists-presents-chanell-stone/|title=MoAD Emerging Artists presents Chanell Stone|website=MoAD Museum of African Diaspora|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> \"Natura Negra\" won her an emerging artist award from the [[Museum of the African Diaspora]] in San Francisco.\n\nStone has also worked as an editorial photographer for the [[The California Sunday Magazine|California Sunday Magazine]], documenting a family affected by the [[Camp Fire (2018)|Camp Fire]] in Paradise, California in 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://story.californiasunday.com/escape-paradise-fires|title=High School Students Escape the Paradise Fire|date=2019-10-03|website=The California Sunday Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>.\n\n== Awards and fellowships ==\nAmong the honors which Stone has earned are:\n\n2020 Artist in Residence, Real Time and Space<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.realtimeandspace.org/residency-2/|title=REAL TIME & SPACE {{!}} RESIDENCY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n2019-2020 Emerging Artist Award, [[Museum of the African Diaspora]] San Francisco<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moadsf.org/connect/emerging-artists-program/|title=Emerging Artists Program|website=MoAD Museum of African Diaspora|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n2018-2019\u00a0 Purchase Prize Award, [[Center for Photography at Woodstock]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cpw.org/news/about-photography-now-2018/|title=CPW \u2014 Photography Now 2018|website=www.cpw.org|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n2018-2019\u00a0 Kate V. and Harry W. Davies Memorial Scholarship, California College of the Arts\n\n2017-2019\u00a0 Diversity Scholarship, California College of the Arts\n\n2017-2019\u00a0 Faculty Honors Scholarship, California College of the Arts\n\n== Selected exhibitions ==\nStone\u2019s work has been featured in exhibitions at numerous galleries and institutions including:\n\n*[http://www.berkeleyartcenter.org/ Berkeley Art Center], Berkeley, CA \u201cExperiments in the Field: Creative Collaboration in the Age of Ecological Concern\u201d (2020)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mutualart.com/Exhibition/Experiments-in-the-Field--Creative-Colla/D74EE38665E0BFEA|title=MutualArt.com - The Web's Largest Art Information Service.|website=www.mutualart.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n*[[Museum of the African Diaspora]], San Francisco, CA, \u201cNatura Negra\u201d (2020)<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n* [[Aperture Foundation]], New York, NY, \u201cAperture Summer Open: Delirious Cities\u201d (2019)\n\n* [[SF Camerawork]], San Francisco, CA, \u201cForecast\u201d (2019)\n\n*[https://www.hitgallerysf.com/ Hit Gallery], San Francisco, CA, \u201cBrass Tacks\u201d (2019)\n\n*[http://www.kala.org/ Kala Art Institute], Berkeley, CA, \u201cPoetics of Conflict\u201d (2018)\n\n* [[Center for Photography at Woodstock]], Woodstock, NY, \u201cPhotography Now\u201d (2018)\n\n*[https://www.oygprojects.com/ Ortega y Gasset Projects], Brooklyn, NY, \u201cVice Versa\u201d (2018)\n\n== Collections ==\nStone's work is held in collections including:\n\n* [[Center for Photography at Woodstock]], Woodstock, NY\n\n* Meyer Library: Artist Book Collection, Oakland, CA\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Official site|https://www.chanellstone.com/}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stone, Chanell}}\n[[Category:American contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:American photographers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women artists]]\n[[Category:Artists from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:California College of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name             = Chanell Stone\n| birth_date       = [[1992]]\n| birth_place      = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n| nationality      = American\n| field            = [[Photography]]\n| alma_mater       = [[California College of the Arts]]\n                   and [[Los Angeles Trade-Technical College]]\n| awards           = 2020 Artist in Residence, Real Time and Space\n2019-2020 Emerging Artist Award, [[Museum of the African Diaspora]], San Francisco\n2018-2019  Purchase Prize Award, [[Center for Photography at Woodstock]]\n| website          = {{URL|https://www.chanellstone.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Chanell Stone''' is an African American [[photographer]] living and working in [[Oakland, California]] known for her \"[https://www.chanellstone.com/natura-negra Natura Negra]\" series.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nStone\u00a0received a [[Bachelor of Fine Arts|B.F.A.]] in [[photography]] from [[California College of the Arts]] in 2019. She received an [[associate degree]] in [[English]] from [[Los Angeles Trade-Technical College]] in 2017. \n\n== Work ==\nChanell Stone's work predominantly features black and white self-portraits. She first took an [[analog photography]] class in high school<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/young-photographers-to-follow-2020/|title=These Are the 8 Young Photographers to Follow in 2020|website=W Magazine {{!}} Women's Fashion & Celebrity News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> and continues to use film in her practice, primarily shooting with a Pentax.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nStone was a featured photographer in [[W (magazine)|W Magazine]]'s \"These Are the 8 Young Photographers to Follow in 2020\".<ref name=\":0\" />  She attributes her interest in representation and self-portraiture to growing up with social media, namely [[Myspace]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nHer series \"Natura Negra\" explores the connection of black bodies and nature, specifically the nature that can be found in dense cities<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/arts/13873630/the-faces-and-conversations-of-moads-winter-2020-opening-reception|title=The Faces and Conversations of MoAD's Winter Opening Reception|website=KQED|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> or what she refers to as \"urban nature\".<ref name=\":0\" /> This series sets out to reclaim and reconnect black bodies to nature, even if it is in an urban setting.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.moadsf.org/exhibition/moad-emerging-artists-presents-chanell-stone/|title=MoAD Emerging Artists presents Chanell Stone|website=MoAD Museum of African Diaspora|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> \"Natura Negra\" won her an emerging artist award from the [[Museum of the African Diaspora]] in San Francisco.\n\nStone has also worked as an editorial photographer for the [[The California Sunday Magazine|California Sunday Magazine]], documenting a family affected by the [[Camp Fire (2018)|Camp Fire]] in Paradise, California in 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://story.californiasunday.com/escape-paradise-fires|title=High School Students Escape the Paradise Fire|date=2019-10-03|website=The California Sunday Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>.\n\n== Awards and fellowships ==\nAmong the honors which Stone has earned are:\n\n2020 Artist in Residence, Real Time and Space<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.realtimeandspace.org/residency-2/|title=REAL TIME & SPACE {{!}} RESIDENCY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n2019-2020 Emerging Artist Award, [[Museum of the African Diaspora]] San Francisco<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moadsf.org/connect/emerging-artists-program/|title=Emerging Artists Program|website=MoAD Museum of African Diaspora|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n2018-2019\u00a0 Purchase Prize Award, [[Center for Photography at Woodstock]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cpw.org/news/about-photography-now-2018/|title=CPW \u2014 Photography Now 2018|website=www.cpw.org|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n2018-2019\u00a0 Kate V. and Harry W. Davies Memorial Scholarship, California College of the Arts\n\n2017-2019\u00a0 Diversity Scholarship, California College of the Arts\n\n2017-2019\u00a0 Faculty Honors Scholarship, California College of the Arts\n\n== Selected exhibitions ==\nStone\u2019s work has been featured in exhibitions at numerous galleries and institutions including:\n\n*[http://www.berkeleyartcenter.org/ Berkeley Art Center], Berkeley, CA \u201cExperiments in the Field: Creative Collaboration in the Age of Ecological Concern\u201d (2020)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mutualart.com/Exhibition/Experiments-in-the-Field--Creative-Colla/D74EE38665E0BFEA|title=MutualArt.com - The Web's Largest Art Information Service.|website=www.mutualart.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n*[[Museum of the African Diaspora]], San Francisco, CA, \u201cNatura Negra\u201d (2020)<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n* [[Aperture Foundation]], New York, NY, \u201cAperture Summer Open: Delirious Cities\u201d (2019)\n\n* [[SF Camerawork]], San Francisco, CA, \u201cForecast\u201d (2019)\n\n*[https://www.hitgallerysf.com/ Hit Gallery], San Francisco, CA, \u201cBrass Tacks\u201d (2019)\n\n*[http://www.kala.org/ Kala Art Institute], Berkeley, CA, \u201cPoetics of Conflict\u201d (2018)\n\n* [[Center for Photography at Woodstock]], Woodstock, NY, \u201cPhotography Now\u201d (2018)\n\n*[https://www.oygprojects.com/ Ortega y Gasset Projects], Brooklyn, NY, \u201cVice Versa\u201d (2018)\n\n== Collections ==\nStone's work is held in collections including:\n\n* [[Center for Photography at Woodstock]], Woodstock, NY\n\n* Meyer Library: Artist Book Collection, Oakland, CA\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==