s Rijsewik, 5 Antonie Boot, 6 Jan Bruin, 7 Frank Kales, 8 Antonius van der Kroon, 9 Karel Pastor, 10 Karel Vrolijk, 11 Erik Jager, 12 Roelof Tuinstra, 13 Erik van Woerkom, 14 Franciscus de Haan, 15 Frederik Witte (Coach: ?)\n----\n'''[[1975 EuroBasket]]:''' finished '''10th''' among 12 teams\n\n4 Jan Dekker, 5 Antonie Boot, 6 Jan Sikking, 7 Hugo Harrewijn, 8 Herman Pluim, 9 Walter Ombre, 10 John van Vliet, 11 [[Kees Akerboom Sr.|Kees Akerboom]], 12 Dan Cramer, 13 [[Toon van Helfteren]], 14 Pieter van Tuyll, 15 Harry Kip (Coach: ?)\n----\n'''[[1977 EuroBasket]]:''' finished '''7th''' among 12 teams\n\n4 Al Faber, 5 Jan Dekker, 6 Jimmy Woudstra, 7 Cees Limmen, 8 Emill Hagens, 9 Bert Kragtwijk, 10 Cock van de Lagemaat, 11 Dan Cramer, 12 [[Kees Akerboom Sr.|Kees Akerboom]], 13 Jan Loorbach, 14 Renso Zwiers, 15 Harry Kip (Coach: ?)\n----\n'''[[1979 EuroBasket]]:''' finished '''10th''' among 12 teams\n\n4 Bert Kragtwijk, 5 Jan Dekker, 6 Dan Cramer, 7 Mitchell Plaat, 8 Emill Hagens, 9 Al Faber, 10 Sid Bruinsma, 11 Jimmy Woudstra, 12 [[Kees Akerboom Sr.|Kees Akerboom]], 13 [[Toon van Helfteren]], 14 Pieter van Tuyll, 15 Harry Kip (Coach: ?) \n----\n'''[[1983 EuroBasket]]:''' finished '''4th''' among 12 teams\n\n4 Ren\u00e9 Ridderhof, 5 Ronald Schilp, 6 Randy Wiel, 7 Mitchell Plaat, 8 Jelle Esveldt, 9 Al Faber, 10 Jos Kuipers, 11 Dan Cramer, 12 Cock van de Lagemaat, 13 Henk Pieterse, 14 Roland van den Bergh, 15 Rob van Essen (Coach: Vladim\u00edr Heger)\t\n----\n'''[[1985 EuroBasket]]:''' finished '''12th''' among 12 teams\n\n4 Martin Esajas, 5 Ronald Schilp, 6 [[Martin de Vries]], 7 Marco de Waard, 8 Jelle Esveldt, 9 Ron van der Schaaf, 10 John Franken, 11 Cock van de Lagemaat, 12 Jos Kuipers, 13 Peter van Noord, 14 Hans Heijdeman, 15 Rob van Essen (Coach: Vladim\u00edr Heger)\n----\n'''[[1986 FIBA World Championship|1986 FIBA World Cup]]:''' finished '''14th''' among 24 teams\n\n4 [[Rik Smits]], 5 Jelle Esveldt, 6 Ronald Schilp, 7 Cock van de Lagemaat, 8 Raymond Bottse, 9 Rene Ebeltjes, 10 Chris van Dinten, 11 Hans Heijdeman, 12 Erik Griekspoor, 13 Emill Hagens, 14 Marco de Waard, 15 Peter van Noord (Coach: Ruud Harrewijn)\n----\n'''[[1987 EuroBasket]]:''' finished '''10th''' among 12 teams\n\n4 John Emanuels, 5 Ronald Schilp, 6 Marco de Waard, 7 Cees van Rootselaar, 8 Jelle Esveldt, 9 Okke te Velde, 10 [[Rik Smits]], 11 Chris van Dinten, 12 Peter van Noord, 13 [[Toon van Helfteren]], 14 Henk Pieterse, 15 Jos Kuipers (Coach: Ruud Harrewijn)\n----\n'''[[1989 EuroBasket]]:''' finished '''8th''' among 8 teams\n\n4 Raymond Bottse, 5 John Emanuels, 6 Marco de Waard, 7 Cees van Rootselaar, 8 Rolf Franke, 9 Okke te Velde, 10 Richard van Poelgeest, 11 Frans Houben, 12 Milko Lieverst, 13 Paul Vrind, 14 Peter Dam, 15 Jos Kuipers (Coach: Ruud Harrewijn)\n----\n'''[[2015 EuroBasket]]:''' finished '''21st''' among 24 teams\n\n0 [[Yannick Franke]], 5 [[Leon Williams (basketball, born 1992)|Leon Williams]], 6 [[Worthy de Jong]], 7 [[Charlon Kloof]], 9 [[Mohamed Kherrazi]], 10 [[Ralf de Pagter]], 12 [[Kees Akerboom, Jr.]], 13 [[Roeland Schaftenaar]], 18 [[Nicolas de Jong]], 21 [[Robin Smeulders]], 23 [[Henk Norel]], 44 [[Arvin Slagter]] '''(C)''' (Coach: [[Toon van Helfteren]])\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sports|Netherlands}}\n*[[Sport in the Netherlands]]\n*[[Netherlands women's national basketball team]]\n*[[Netherlands national under-19 basketball team]]\n*[[Netherlands national under-17 basketball team]]\n*[[Dutch Basketball League]] (DBL)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Netherlands men's national basketball team}}\n*[http://www.basketball.nl/ Official website] {{in lang|nl}}\n*[http://www.fiba.basketball/federation/Netherlands Netherlands] at FIBA site\n*[http://www.eurobasket.com/Holland/basketball-National-Team.asp Dutch National Team - Men] at Eurobasket.com\n*[http://www.fiba.basketball/pages/eng/fa/p/rpp//tid/334/_//teams.html Netherlands Basketball Records] at FIBA Archive\n\n{{National sports teams of the Netherlands}}\n{{FIBA Europe teams}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Netherlands National Basketball Team}}\n[[Category:National basketball teams]]\n[[Category:Basketball in the Netherlands| ]]\n[[Category:National sports teams of the Netherlands|Basketball]]\n[[Category:1946 establishments in the Netherlands]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the men's team|the women's team|Netherlands women's national basketball team}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox national basketball team\n| country           = Netherlands {{flagicon|NED}}\n| logo              = Basketball Nederland logo.png \n| logo_width        = 180px\n| nickname          = ''Oranje'' (Orange)\n| coach             = [[Maurizio Buscaglia]]\n| fiba_ranking      = {{FIBA World Rankings|NED}}\n| joined_FIBA       = 1946\n| fiba_zone         = FIBA Europe\n| national_fed      = [[Basketball Nederland]]\n| oly_appearances   = None\n| oly_medals        = \n| wc_appearances    = '''1''' ([[1986 FIBA World Championship|1986]])\n| wc_medals         = None\n| zone_championship = [[EuroBasket]]\n| zone_appearances  = 15\n| zone_medals       = None\n| h_body            = FF5800\n| h_title           = Home\n| h_pattern_b       = _black_nzfc_shoulders\n| h_shorts          = FF5800\n| h_pattern_s       = \n| a_title           = Away\n| a_body            = FFFFFF\n| a_pattern_b       =  _black_nzfc_shoulders\n| a_shorts          = FFFFFF\n| a_pattern_s       = \n| first_game        = \n| largest_win       = \n| largest_loss      = \n}}\n\nThe '''Netherlands national basketball team''' ({{lang-nl|Het Nederlands Elftal}}) represents the [[Netherlands]] in international [[basketball]] matches. The national team is governed by [[Basketball Nederland]]. \n\nThe Dutch have reached the [[EuroBasket|European Basketball Championship]] on 15 occasions. Their best results at the event came in [[EuroBasket 1983|1983]], where they finished in fourth place. They have also qualified for the [[FIBA World Cup]] once, in [[1986 FIBA World Championship|1986]]. In recent years though, the national team has struggled to maintain consistency to reach major international tournaments.\n\nThe team represents itself as the '''Orange Lions'''.\n\n==History==\n===1946\u20131991: Early years===\n[[File:Basketbal Nederland tegen Luxemburg in Apollohal Amsterdam, Bestanddeelnr 910-8505.jpg|thumb|left|200px|The Netherlands playing a match against [[Luxembourg national basketball team|Luxembourg]] in 1959]]\nThe Netherlands were one of the teams that played in the [[EuroBasket 1946|1946]], [[EuroBasket 1947|1947]], [[EuroBasket 1949|1949]] and [[EuroBasket 1951|1951]] EuroBasket tournaments. During this period, the 5th place finish in 1949 was the best performance by the national team.\n\n===1961\u20131991: EuroBasket success & World Cup debut===\nThe ''Oranje'' qualified for three [[European Basketball Championships]] in the 1960s ([[EuroBasket 1961|1961]], [[EuroBasket 1963|1963]], [[EuroBasket 1967|1967]]). After three consecutive missed tournaments, the Netherlands had another three EuroBasket appearance stretch from [[EuroBasket 1975|1975]], [[EuroBasket 1977|1977]], and [[EuroBasket 1979|1979]]. During the 1977 EuroBasket, the Netherlands' star player [[Kees Akerboom Sr.|Kees Akerboom]] shined during the tournament. He finished the competition as the top scorer, and earned a spot on the All-Tournament Team.\n\nAt [[EuroBasket 1983]], the Dutch had its biggest success in history under head coach Vladimir Heger. The national team achieved fourth place at the tournament. The Dutch wound up reaching the semi-finals, but eventually fell to [[Italy national basketball team|Italy]]. In the third-place game they would lose again, this time to the [[Soviet Union national basketball team|Soviet Union]].\n\nThree years after achieving success at the continental level, the Netherlands qualified to the [[FIBA Basketball World Cup|World Cup]] for the first time in [[1986 FIBA World Championship|1986]]. The national team ultimately did not make it out of the group stage though, finishing the tournament with an (2-3) record to place 14th overall.\n\n===1991\u20132012: Long mediocre period===\n[[File:Francisco Elson.jpg|thumb|180px|right|[[Francisco Elson]] was the face of the team for a long time]]\nFrom 1991 until 2012, the Netherlands did not qualify for a EuroBasket tournament. Star player [[Francisco Elson]], former [[NBA]]-champion, represented the team on several occasions but the team never came close to qualifying. During this period, notable Dutch players like [[Dan Gadzuric]] were not willing to play for the national team. Home games were usually played at the [[Topsportcentrum (Almere)|Topsportcentrum]] in [[Almere]] and usually had little to no media attention or fan support in the Netherlands.\n\n===Rising from the ashes (2012\u20132015)===\n[[File:Toon van Helfteren.jpg|thumb|172px|[[Toon van Helfteren]] coached the national team to its first EuroBasket tournament in 26 years]]\nIn December 2012, it was announced that the Netherlands national team would be dissolved for 2 years, because the national federation NBB {Netherlands Basketball Bond} was not willing to invest money in to it. After an campaign by Dutch players who played in the [[Dutch Basketball League]], the national team was eventually saved. Sports broadcaster [[Sport1 (Netherlands)|Sport1]] became the main sponsor and DBL-teams invested in the team, which started playing again.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/2698/Sport/article/detail/3359327/2012/12/06/Nederlandse-basketballers-gered-door-Sport1.dhtml |title=Nederlandse basketballers gered door Sport1 | language = Dutch |work=Volkskrant.nl |date= |accessdate=2014-06-15}}</ref>\n\nDuring August 2013, the Netherlands was on its way to qualification for [[EuroBasket 2015]], but lost two games 20\u20130 because the team played with two players  \u2013 [[Mohamed Kherrazi]] and [[Sean Cunningham (basketball)|Sean Cunningham]] \u2013 who were identified as foreign players by [[FIBA]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fibaeurope.com/coid_kFXfIOeXHlsnHUTnR72dF2.articleMode_on.html |title=Netherlands Incur Penalty |work=FIBA Europe |date= |accessdate=2014-06-15}}</ref> The NBB believed that both were eligible players, and was upset that the attention came up after the Netherlands already won 2 games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nos.nl/artikel/540247-nbb-niet-eens-met-straf.html |title=NBB niet eens met straf |work = NOS |date= |accessdate=2014-06-15}}</ref>\n\n===\"Miracle of 2014\"===\n[[File:Netherlands basketball team logo.png|150px|thumb|left|Logo used from 2012\u20132019]]\nAt the start of the second 2015-qualification round, things looked bad for the ''Oranje''. The DBL-teams didn't have any more money to invest in the team and the NBB  wasn't ready to take the team back. Head coach [[Toon van Helfteren]], who worked as a volunteer, still did prepare for the qualifying games. He invited 42 players to play for the national team,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketballleague.nl/nieuws/552 |title=Eredivisie basketbal Nederland |publisher=Basketballleague.nl |date= |accessdate=2015-01-16}}</ref> but after most (notable) players rejected the offer, he started his first training camp with 7 players. The team eventually shocked the world, by beating heavy favorite [[Montenegro national basketball team|Montenegro]] to get the second place in their group. On 27 August 2014, the Dutch national team qualified for EuroBasket for the first time in 25 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nos.nl/artikel/691692-basketballers-na-25-jaar-naar-ek.html |title=Basketballers na 25 jaar naar EK |publisher=Nos.nl |date= |accessdate=2015-01-16}}</ref>\n\n===Return to EuroBasket (2015\u2013present)===\nThe national team left the NBB and FEB, from 2015 the team was run by the NMT. Coach Van Helfteren then had his contract with the national team extended. In contrast to the summer of 2014, big name players from foreign leagues applied to play for the national team.\n\nIn the first game at [[EuroBasket 2015]], the Dutch beat [[Georgian national basketball team|Georgia]] 73\u201372 behind [[Charlon Kloof]]'s 22 and [[Worthy de Jong]]'s 16 points.<ref>[http://www.eurobasket2015.org/en/compID_qMRZdYCZI6EoANOrUf9le2.season_2015.roundID_9322.coid_1bM7BSWJHos6LdZ2wq4,A3.articleMode_on.1_1.html Dutch Win On Return]</ref> The Netherlands remaining four games though were all loses, but only by single digits to power houses such as [[Croatia men's national basketball team|Croatia]] and [[Greece national basketball team|Greece]].\n\nOn 22 July 2019, Italian coach [[Maurizio Buscaglia]] signed a contract to become the head coach of the Netherlands, ending in the summer of 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oranjebasketball.com/nieuws/berichten/italiaan-buscaglia-nieuwe-basketballcoach-nederlands-mannenteam/|title=Italiaan Buscaglia nieuwe basketballcoach Nederlands mannenteam|date=22 July 2019|work=Oranje Basketball|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref> \n\n==Competitive record==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n\n===EuroBasket===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;font-size:90%;\"\n!colspan=5|[[EuroBasket]]\n!rowspan=41|\n!colspan=3|Qualification\n|-\n!Year\n!Position\n!width=30|{{Tooltip|Pld|Games played}}\n!width=30|{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!width=30|{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!width=30|{{Tooltip|Pld|Games played}}\n!width=30|{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!width=30|{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n|-\n|{{flagicon|SUI}} [[EuroBasket 1946|1946]]||6th||3||1||2\n|-\n|{{flagicon|TCH}} [[EuroBasket 1947|1947]]||11th||6||2||4\n|-\n|{{flagicon|EGY|1922}} [[EuroBasket 1949|1949]]||5th||6||2||4\n|-\n|{{flagicon|FRA|1830}} [[EuroBasket 1951|1951]]||10th||9||5||4\n|-\n|{{flagicon|USSR|1936}} [[EuroBasket 1953|1953]]||colspan=4 rowspan=4|''Did not enter''\n|-\n|{{flagicon|HUN|1949}} [[EuroBasket 1955|1955]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|BUL|1946}} [[EuroBasket 1957|1957]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|TUR}} [[EuroBasket 1959|1959]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|YUG}} [[EuroBasket 1961|